WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.600
 Hello and welcome to my lecture on the mini Django web server. So why did I

00:00:05.600 --> 00:00:10.520
 build this mini Django web server? Well, the first part of my Django for everybody

00:00:10.520 --> 00:00:16.700
 course is always about getting students to understand the nature of Django. If you

00:00:16.700 --> 00:00:20.400
 know how to use Django and you know how it works internally, it's easy to write

00:00:20.400 --> 00:00:24.860
 web applications because Django takes care of all the details of hypertext

00:00:24.860 --> 00:00:31.600
 transfer protocol, HTTP. And you can read documents, tons of documents, hundreds and

00:00:31.600 --> 00:00:38.640
 thousands of pages, and write your own Python code to handle the HTTP. The

00:00:38.640 --> 00:00:42.520
 problem though is, while Django makes it so you don't have to read any of that, you

00:00:42.520 --> 00:00:46.680
 do have to understand Django. And Django, to give you the kind of flexibility that

00:00:46.680 --> 00:00:52.080
 you need, uses a very object-oriented inversion of control, a whole bunch of

00:00:52.080 --> 00:00:55.240
 design patterns that make it so you don't have to write the whole

00:00:55.240 --> 00:01:01.400
 application, but you need to plug your work into Django. So it's important for

00:01:01.400 --> 00:01:06.480
 you to understand what the framework is and how it is that your work fits into

00:01:06.480 --> 00:01:13.920
 it. So mini Django is the simplest possible Django that I could write. It's

00:01:13.920 --> 00:01:18.600
 under 200 lines. The mini Django framework itself is only 200 lines of

00:01:18.600 --> 00:01:23.240
 Python, meaning you can read it, you can understand it, and you can even change it

00:01:23.240 --> 00:01:28.520
 and explore supporting additional features of HTTP. So we're gonna build

00:01:28.520 --> 00:01:35.000
 both have a mini Django and a really simple Django-like application. So why do

00:01:35.000 --> 00:01:41.360
 we use Django in the first place? Like I said, do you really want to read RFC 7231?

00:01:41.360 --> 00:01:47.320
 It is pages that's over a hundred pages and it's detail upon detail upon detail.

00:01:47.320 --> 00:01:52.560
 If you start reading it, you will realize it's really well-defined how browsers and

00:01:52.560 --> 00:01:57.680
 web servers talk, but you really don't want to read it, especially when someone

00:01:57.680 --> 00:02:02.600
 else has written all the code. And all you have to do is import HTTP request and

00:02:02.600 --> 00:02:08.040
 response from Django.http and then write a four-line function that takes as its

00:02:08.040 --> 00:02:13.560
 input an HTTP request and returns an HTTP response. And then in your code you

00:02:13.560 --> 00:02:18.480
 create the HTTP response and put some text in it and you return it and then

00:02:18.480 --> 00:02:26.240
 Django literally outside of your code does everything else. So Django takes this

00:02:26.240 --> 00:02:30.760
 super complex task and hides it behind an abstraction. It's something, an

00:02:30.760 --> 00:02:35.320
 abstraction is something you're sort of not supposed to look past. You're

00:02:35.320 --> 00:02:38.640
 supposed to just look at the interface that it gives to you and you're supposed

00:02:38.640 --> 00:02:42.680
 to express your logic and then plug it in at the right place to create a rich

00:02:42.680 --> 00:02:47.760
 and HTTP compliant web application. Django handles all the details and there's

00:02:47.760 --> 00:02:53.240
 lots of them, thousands and thousands of little detail. But with all abstractions

00:02:53.240 --> 00:02:57.240
 it's a good idea to understand the shape of the abstraction that you're dealing

00:02:57.240 --> 00:03:01.120
 with so you can kind of have some predictability as to when you make a

00:03:01.120 --> 00:03:06.320
 change to your code. How is that? And then Django says do this, override this

00:03:06.320 --> 00:03:12.240
 method, override the query method, all that stuff. You have to

00:03:12.240 --> 00:03:17.680
 kind of understand what's going on behind the scenes. And so my hope is is

00:03:17.680 --> 00:03:22.160
 that if you can understand mini Django you'll better have a chance, it'll have a

00:03:22.160 --> 00:03:28.680
 much better chance of understanding the real Django. So in my class I use this

00:03:28.680 --> 00:03:33.320
 thing I call the big picture and on the left side is a browser with a document

00:03:33.320 --> 00:03:39.200
 object model that deals with HTML and CSS and JavaScript and intercept user

